\code{v_max(Omega_s)} whenever \verb{|lambda_max| > |lambda_min|} (the typical
case for Mercer-PSD or near-PSD matrices). This implementation uses the
standard two-pass shifted power iteration: Pass 1 estimates
\code{lambda_max} via power iteration on \code{Omega_s}; Pass 2 estimates
\code{lambda_min} via power iteration on \code{rho * I - Omega_s} (whose
dominant eigenvector is \code{v_min(Omega_s)}). Both passes are O(N^2); the
total cost is \code{2 * T_pi} matvecs.

The Pass 2 shift uses the spectral radius \verb{rho = |Pass 1 Rayleigh|},
not Pass 1's signed Rayleigh. This handles the \code{lambda_min}-dominant
pathological case (\verb{|lambda_min| > lambda_max}), where plain power
iteration on \code{Omega_s} in Pass 1 converges to \code{v_min} and gives a
negative Rayleigh; using \verb{abs(Pass 1 Rayleigh)} ensures the shifted
operator \code{rho * I - Omega_s} is PSD, so Pass 2 reliably finds
\code{v_min(Omega_s)} regardless of which side of the spectrum dominated
Pass 1.
